{"title_page": "Kriszti\u00e1n Kenesei", "text_new": "{{Eastern name order|Kenesei Kriszti\u00e1n}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Kriszti\u00e1n Kenesei\n| fullname    = Kriszti\u00e1n Kenesei\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1977|1|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]]\n| height      = {{convert|1.78|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position    = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub = [[Vasas SC|Vasas]]\n| clubnumber  = 20\n| years1 = 1993\u20132000  | clubs1 = [[MTK Budapest FC|MTK]]             | caps1 = 177 | goals1 =  67\n| years2 = 2000\u20132001  | clubs2 = [[Gy\u0151ri ETO FC|Gy\u0151r]]               | caps2 =  30 | goals2 =  15\n| years3 = 2001\u20132003  | clubs3 = [[Zalaegerszegi TE|Zalaegerszeg]]   | caps3 =  68 | goals3 =  44\n| years4 = 2003\u20132006  | clubs4 = [[Beijing Guoan]]                   | caps4 =  36 | goals4 =  12\n| years5 = 2005       | clubs5 = \u2192  [[Gy\u0151ri ETO FC|Gy\u0151r]] (loan)     | caps5 =  28 | goals5 =  14\n| years6 = 2007       | clubs6 = [[Vasas SC|Vasas]]                  | caps6 =  10 | goals6 =   6\n| years7 = 2007\u20132008  | clubs7 = [[U.S. Avellino 1912|Avellino]]     | caps7 =  22 | goals7 =   8\n| years8 = 2008\u20132013  | clubs8 = [[Szombathelyi Halad\u00e1s|Halad\u00e1s]]    | caps8 =  92 | goals8 =  42\n| years9 = 2013\u20132015  | clubs9 = [[Lombard-P\u00e1pa TFC|P\u00e1pa]]           | caps9 =  36 | goals9 =   5\n| years10 = 2015      | clubs10 = [[Vasas SC|Vasas]]                 | caps10 = 19 | goals10 =  4\n| years11 = 2016\u20132018 | clubs11 = [[III. Ker\u00fcleti TVE|III. Ker\u00fclet]] | caps11 = 52 | goals11 = 30\n| years12 = 2018\u20132020 | clubs12 = [[Kom\u00e1rom VSE|Kom\u00e1rom]]            | caps12 = 43 | goals12 = 17\n| nationalyears1 = 1996\u20131999 | nationalteam1 = [[Hungary national under-21 football team|Hungary U-21]] | nationalcaps1 =  4 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2000\u20132005 | nationalteam2 = [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]]               | nationalcaps2 = 30 | nationalgoals2 = 9\n}}\n\n'''Kriszti\u00e1n Kenesei''' (born 7 January 1977) is a Hungarian former professional [[association football|footballer]].\n\n== Club career ==\nKenesei started his career at [[MTK Hung\u00e1ria FC|MTK Hung\u00e1ria]], where he played 9 years. He then moved to [[Gy\u0151ri ETO FC|Gy\u0151ri ETO]] and [[Zalaegerszeg]], before signed by [[Beijing Guoan]] on 25 August 2003. He was offered a 3-year contract at the end of 2003 season. Kenesei was loaned back to [[Gy\u0151ri ETO FC|Gy\u0151ri ETO]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/footballeurope/news/kind=2/newsid=278930.html|title=Hungary hope for starring role|date=10 February 2005|work=UEFA.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, he was allowed to sign by [[Vasas SC|Vasas]], and on 30 July 2007, he was signed by newly promoted Serie B team [[U.S. Avellino 1912|Avellino]]. For the 2008/09 season he will play for [[Szombathelyi Halad\u00e1s]].\n\n==International career==\nKenesei played for [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] but after he returned to China in 2006 he did not receive any call-up. Kenesei played 7 games in [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying]].<ref>http://www.weltfussball.de/spieler_profil/krisztian-kenesei/4/</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n===Club===\n'''[[MTK Budapest FC]]'''<ref name=\"Kenesei, Kriszti\u00e1n\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.national-football-teams.com/player/3014/Krisztian_Kenesei.html|title=Kenesei, Kriszti\u00e1n|publisher=National-football-teams.com |date=2019-08-22 |accessdate=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n*[[Hungarian League]]: [[Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I 1996-97|1996\u201397]], [[Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I 1998-99|1998\u201399]]\n*[[Hungarian Cup]]: [[1996\u201397 Magyar Kupa|1996\u201397]], [[1997\u201398 Magyar Kupa|1997\u201398]], [[1999\u20132000 Magyar Kupa|1999\u201300]]\n\n'''[[Zalaegerszegi TE|Zalaegerszeg]]'''<ref name=\"Kenesei, Kriszti\u00e1n\"/>\n*[[Hungarian League]]: [[2001\u201302 Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I|2001\u201302]]\n\n'''[[Beijing Guoan]]'''<ref name=\"Kenesei, Kriszti\u00e1n\"/>\n*[[Chinese FA Cup]]: [[2003 Chinese FA Cup|2003]]\n*[[Chinese Super Cup]]: [[2003 Chinese Football Super Cup|2003]]\n\n===Individual===\n*Hungarian Top scorer: [[2002\u201303 Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I|2002\u201303]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{FIFA player|169694}}\n*{{NFT player|pid=3014}}\n*[http://www.magyarfutball.hu/hu/szemelyek/adatlap/408 Kriszti\u00e1n Kenesei profile at magyarfutball.hu]\n*[http://sports.sina.com.cn/star/kenesei/index.shtml Profile at Sina] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[http://www.gazzetta.it/speciali/serie_b/2008_nw/giocatori/73096.shtml Profile at gazzetta.it] {{in lang|it}}\n\n{{Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I top scorers}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kenesei, Krisztian}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Budapest]]\n[[Category:Hungarian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Hungary international footballers]]\n[[Category:Hungary under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:MTK Budapest FC players]]\n[[Category:Gy\u0151ri ETO FC players]]\n[[Category:Zalaegerszegi TE players]]\n[[Category:Beijing Guoan F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Vasas FC players]]\n[[Category:U.S. Avellino 1912 players]]\n[[Category:Szombathelyi Halad\u00e1s footballers]]\n[[Category:Lombard-P\u00e1pa TFC footballers]]\n[[Category:Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Chinese Super League players]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in China]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in China]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:III. Ker\u00fcleti TUE footballers]]\n[[Category:Kom\u00e1romi FC footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Eastern name order|Kenesei Kriszti\u00e1n}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Kriszti\u00e1n Kenesei\n| fullname    = Kriszti\u00e1n Kenesei\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1977|1|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]]\n| height      = {{convert|1.78|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position    = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub = [[Vasas SC|Vasas]]\n| clubnumber  = 20\n| years1 = 1993\u20132000  | clubs1 = [[MTK Budapest FC|MTK]]             | caps1 = 177 | goals1 =  67\n| years2 = 2000\u20132001  | clubs2 = [[Gy\u0151ri ETO FC|Gy\u0151r]]               | caps2 =  30 | goals2 =  15\n| years3 = 2001\u20132003  | clubs3 = [[Zalaegerszegi TE|Zalaegerszeg]]   | caps3 =  68 | goals3 =  44\n| years4 = 2003\u20132006  | clubs4 = [[Beijing Guoan]]                   | caps4 =  36 | goals4 =  12\n| years5 = 2005       | clubs5 = \u2192  [[Gy\u0151ri ETO FC|Gy\u0151r]] (loan)     | caps5 =  28 | goals5 =  14\n| years6 = 2007       | clubs6 = [[Vasas SC|Vasas]]                  | caps6 =  10 | goals6 =   6\n| years7 = 2007\u20132008  | clubs7 = [[U.S. Avellino 1912|Avellino]]     | caps7 =  22 | goals7 =   8\n| years8 = 2008\u20132013  | clubs8 = [[Szombathelyi Halad\u00e1s|Halad\u00e1s]]    | caps8 =  92 | goals8 =  42\n| years9 = 2013\u20132015  | clubs9 = [[Lombard-P\u00e1pa TFC|P\u00e1pa]]           | caps9 =  36 | goals9 =   5\n| years10 = 2015      | clubs10 = [[Vasas SC|Vasas]]                 | caps10 = 19 | goals10 =  4\n| years11 = 2016\u20132018 | clubs11 = [[III. Ker\u00fcleti TVE|III. Ker\u00fclet]] | caps11 = 52 | goals11 = 30\n| years12 = 2018\u20132020 | clubs12 = [[Kom\u00e1rom VSE|Kom\u00e1rom]]            | caps12 = 43 | goals12 = 17\n| nationalyears1 = 1996\u20131999 | nationalteam1 = [[Hungary national under-21 football team|Hungary U-21]] | nationalcaps1 =  4 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2000\u20132005 | nationalteam2 = [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]]               | nationalcaps2 = 30 | nationalgoals2 = 9\n}}\n\n'''Kriszti\u00e1n Kenesei''' (born 7 January 1977 in [[Budapest]]) is a retired [[Hungary|Hungarian]] international [[Football (soccer)|football]] player. \n\n== Club career ==\nKenesei started his career at [[MTK Hung\u00e1ria FC|MTK Hung\u00e1ria]], where he played 9 years. He then moved to [[Gy\u0151ri ETO FC|Gy\u0151ri ETO]] and [[Zalaegerszeg]], before signed by [[Beijing Guoan]] on 25 August 2003. He was offered a 3-year contract at the end of 2003 season. Kenesei was loaned back to [[Gy\u0151ri ETO FC|Gy\u0151ri ETO]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/footballeurope/news/kind=2/newsid=278930.html|title=Hungary hope for starring role|date=10 February 2005|work=UEFA.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, he was allowed to sign by [[Vasas SC|Vasas]], and on 30 July 2007, he was signed by newly promoted Serie B team [[U.S. Avellino 1912|Avellino]]. For the 2008/09 season he will play for [[Szombathelyi Halad\u00e1s]].\n\n==International career==\nKenesei played for [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] but after he returned to China in 2006 he did not receive any call-up. Kenesei played 7 games in [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying]].<ref>http://www.weltfussball.de/spieler_profil/krisztian-kenesei/4/</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n===Club===\n'''[[MTK Budapest FC]]'''<ref name=\"Kenesei, Kriszti\u00e1n\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.national-football-teams.com/player/3014/Krisztian_Kenesei.html|title=Kenesei, Kriszti\u00e1n|publisher=National-football-teams.com |date=2019-08-22 |accessdate=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n*[[Hungarian League]]: [[Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I 1996-97|1996\u201397]], [[Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I 1998-99|1998\u201399]]\n*[[Hungarian Cup]]: [[1996\u201397 Magyar Kupa|1996\u201397]], [[1997\u201398 Magyar Kupa|1997\u201398]], [[1999\u20132000 Magyar Kupa|1999\u201300]]\n\n'''[[Zalaegerszegi TE|Zalaegerszeg]]'''<ref name=\"Kenesei, Kriszti\u00e1n\"/>\n*[[Hungarian League]]: [[2001\u201302 Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I|2001\u201302]]\n\n'''[[Beijing Guoan]]'''<ref name=\"Kenesei, Kriszti\u00e1n\"/>\n*[[Chinese FA Cup]]: [[2003 Chinese FA Cup|2003]]\n*[[Chinese Super Cup]]: [[2003 Chinese Football Super Cup|2003]]\n\n===Individual===\n*Hungarian Top scorer: [[2002\u201303 Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I|2002\u201303]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{FIFA player|169694}}\n*{{NFT player|pid=3014}}\n*[http://www.magyarfutball.hu/hu/szemelyek/adatlap/408 Kriszti\u00e1n Kenesei profile at magyarfutball.hu]\n*[http://sports.sina.com.cn/star/kenesei/index.shtml Profile at Sina] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[http://www.gazzetta.it/speciali/serie_b/2008_nw/giocatori/73096.shtml Profile at gazzetta.it] {{in lang|it}}\n\n{{Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I top scorers}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kenesei, Krisztian}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Budapest]]\n[[Category:Hungarian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Hungary international footballers]]\n[[Category:Hungary under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:MTK Budapest FC players]]\n[[Category:Gy\u0151ri ETO FC players]]\n[[Category:Zalaegerszegi TE players]]\n[[Category:Beijing Guoan F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Vasas FC players]]\n[[Category:U.S. Avellino 1912 players]]\n[[Category:Szombathelyi Halad\u00e1s footballers]]\n[[Category:Lombard-P\u00e1pa TFC footballers]]\n[[Category:Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Chinese Super League players]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in China]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in China]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:III. Ker\u00fcleti TUE footballers]]\n[[Category:Kom\u00e1romi FC footballers]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kriszti%C3%A1n_Kenesei"}
{"title_page": "New Brighton, New Zealand", "text_new": "{{short description|Coastal suburb of Christchurch, NZ}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{advert|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n|name                   = New Brighton\n|image_skyline          = New Brighton Pier, Christchurch.jpg\n|image_caption          = New Brighton Pier, Christchurch\n|pushpin_map            = New Zealand Christchurch\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|area_total_km2         = 2.7891\n|population_as_of       = 2013\n|population_total       = 2442\n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|coordinates            = {{coord|-43.508|172.726|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''New Brighton''' is a coastal suburb of [[Christchurch]], New Zealand, {{convert|8|km|mi}} east of the [[Christchurch Central City|city centre]]. At the 2013 census, it had a population of 2,442. The [[Christchurch earthquake]]s caused significant damage in the area.\n\nNew Brighton is one of eastern Christchurch's main entertainment and tourist centres, with its architecturally unique pier and scenic coastline.\n\n==Naming==\nThe naming of New Brighton was apparently done on a 'spur of moment' decision by William Fee, an early settler of the area. When [[Guise Brittan]], the Waste Lands Commissioner, visited the area in December 1860, he was recognised and Fee chalked 'New Brighton' on a wooden plank, supposedly in reference to his fellow settler Stephen Brooker, who had come from [[New Brighton, Merseyside|New Brighton]] in England.<ref name=\"Christchurch Place Names\">{{cite web|last= Harper|first= Margaret|title= Christchurch Place Names|url= http://christchurchcitylibraries.com/Heritage/PlaceNames/ChristchurchPlaceNames.pdf |publisher=Christchurch City Libraries|accessdate=1 October 2011|date=July 2011|pages = 131f}}</ref> The [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] name for the area is Kaiuau (''kai'' means food and ''aua'' is [[Yellow-eye mullet]])<ref name=\"Reed\">{{cite book\n |last=Reed\n |first=A. W.\n |title=Place Names of New Zealand\n |year=2010\n |publisher=Raupo\n |location=Rosedale, North Shore\n |isbn=978-0-14-320410-7\n |page = 45\n |editor=Peter Dowling\n}}</ref> or O-ruapaeroa (an east wind blowing along the shore).<ref name=\"Christchurch Place Names\" />\n\nThe suburb is frequently referred to simply as Brighton, occasionally leading to confusion with [[Brighton, New Zealand|Brighton]] near [[Dunedin]].\n\n==New Brighton Pier==\n{{main|New Brighton Pier}}\n[[File:New Brighton Pier, New Brighton, New Zealand 02.jpg|thumb|New Brighton Pier in evening light in 2019]]\nThere have been two piers in New Brighton. The first pier, of wooden construction, opened on 18 January 1894 and was demolished on 12 October 1965. The current concrete pier was opened on 1 November 1997.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Brighton Pier |url=http://my.christchurchcitylibraries.com/new-brighton-pier/ |publisher=[[Christchurch City Libraries]] |accessdate=23 April 2016}}</ref> It is one of the icons of Christchurch. The pier was closed for earthquake repairs in 2016 reopened again in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/104337314/new-brighton-pier-reopens-on-saturday-following-85-million-repair|title=New Brighton Pier reopens on Saturday following $8.5 million repair|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe suburb is divided into three sections spread along the southern coast of [[Pegasus Bay]]: North New Brighton; New Brighton; and South New Brighton, which lies at the northern end of a narrow peninsula between the bay and the [[Avon Heathcote Estuary]]. A {{convert|300|m|ft}} [[pier]] was built here in the 1990s, and opened on 1 November 1997.\n\nNew Brighton was originally a distinct coastal village, separated from the then outer suburbs of Christchurch by the swampy areas adjoining the [[Avon River (Canterbury)|Avon River]]. However, urban expansion, land reclamation and drainage have led to Brighton being swallowed by Christchurch city.\n\n==Attractions==\n[[File:New Brighton and the Port Hills, Christchurch, New Zealand, 12 June 2008.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Aerial view of New Brighton beach and the Port Hills]]\n[[File:New Brighton, Christchurch.jpg|thumb|200px|The beach]]\nThe current attractions of the area include:\n* A sandy beach, suitable for surfing, stretching 18&nbsp;km from the [[Waimakariri River]] mouth in the north, to the spit in the south\n* New Brighton's Seaside Market \u2013 held weekly in the pedestrian part of the New Brighton Mall\n* Pier and Council library on the foreshore, in Central New Brighton\n* The New Brighton and Districts Museum, located on Hardy Street\n* Home of the first surf life saving club in New Zealand established in 1910,<ref>{{cite web|title=Centenary|url=http://newbrightonslsc.org.nz/?page_id=16|publisher=New Brighton Surf Bathing & Life Saving Club Incorporated 1910|accessdate=1 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312103442/http://newbrightonslsc.org.nz/?page_id=16|archivedate=12 March 2012}}</ref> also North Beach Surf Club to the north and South New Brighton Surf Club to the south\n* Rawhiti Domain \u2013 with a [[Christchurch City Council]]-run golf links, tennis courts, dog park, rugby fields, cricket ovals, netball courts, community carden, archery club and children's play area\n\n[[Image:NewBrightonPier gobeirne.JPG|left|thumb|400px|New Brighton Pier, library, and clock tower]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Events==\nNew Brighton host a variety of free public events:\n\n===Coast to Coast===\n\nStaged every February, the annual Coast to Coast race finishes at New Brighton. Competitors traverse the island by running, canoeing and cycling.\n\n===New Zealand Sand Castle competition===\n\nHeld in February annually.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n===Kite Day===\n\nHeld in January annually.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n===New Brighton day===\n\nEvery February annually, Happy New Brighton Day is one of the largest community events held in New Brighton.\n\n===Guy Fawkes===\n\nThis is held in November annually. There is a display of Fireworks on the New Brighton Pier, beginning at sunset about 9.00pm, as well as a lights show off the pier and music.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n==Saturday trading==\nFor several decades, New Brighton had the distinction of being the only place in Christchurch where general retail shops were permitted to open on Saturdays<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.christchurch.org.nz/Heritage/Chronology/Year/1946.asp|title=Christchurch \u2013 A Chronology \u2013 1946|publisher=[[Christchurch City Libraries]]|accessdate=14 October 2007}}</ref> (remaining closed on Mondays), and the business district thrived as a result. With the introduction of nationwide Saturday trading in 1980, and then seven-day trading in 1990, retail activity declined significantly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/Places/Canterbury/CanterburyPlaces/9/en |title=East Christchurch|publisher=[[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]] |accessdate=14 October 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Walrond |first1=Carl |title=Food shops \u2013 Shopping hours |url= http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/food-shops/page-7 |publisher=Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand |accessdate=16 October 2014 |date=13 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public transport==\nA variety of bus routes connect the city centre with New Brighton.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.metroinfo.co.nz/map/ |title=Metro |publisher=Metroinfo | access-date=22 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nAs of 2015 there are four operating primary schools in New Brighton. This includes New Brighton Catholic and Rawhiti beach campus in central New Brighton, South New Brighton primary in the south New Brighton and Rawhiti QE2 base in North New Brighton. In early 2015, the Christchurch City Council and the Ministry of Education announced that North New Brighton's QE2 park would be accommodating the new 80 million dollar joint secondary school campus consisting of Shirley Boys and Avonside Girls high schools, along the 39 million dollar Eastern Recreation and sports facility. 2015<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Mayor-not-offended-by-cheeky-protest/tabid/423/articleID/278912/Default.aspx|work=3 News NZ |title= Mayor not offended by 'cheeky' protest| date=3 December 2012| accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Sport and recreation==\nA number of well known sports groups represent the local area. Some of the most notable groups are the New Brighton Rugby club. The New Brighton cricket club and the New Brighton Olympic Athletic club. Other groups include the Christchurch Archery club and New Brighton long boarders club. Also home of the oldest Surf Life Saving Club in New Zealand, The New Brighton Surf Bathing & Life Saving Club, established in 1910.\n\n==Christchurch earthquakes aftermath==\nDue in part to the ground on which it was built, the consequences for New Brighton of the 2011 earthquake did not only relate to building damage.\n[[File:Fish and Chip shop North New Brighton, Christchurch following Feb 2011 quake.jpg|thumb|200px|Fish and Chip shop North New Brighton, Christchurch following Feb 2011 quake]]\n[[File:Liquefaction on roads - North New Brighton centre in Christchurch Feb 2011 quake.jpg|thumb|200px|Liquefaction on roads \u2013 North New Brighton centre in Christchurch Feb 2011 quake]]\nIn December 2012 residents held a protest against the perceived slow progress of rebuilding in the area following [[2011 Christchurch earthquake|the region's damaging earthquakes]], in which 80 people bared their bottoms.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/New-Brighton-residents-protest-bum-deal/tabid/423/articleID/278860/Default.aspx |work=3 News NZ |title= Angry residents hold 'cheeky' protest| date=2 December 2012| accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref> Christchurch Mayor Bob Parker said he wasn't offended, but the residents were \"wrong\". These feelings of neglect by the Christchurch City Council would continue to persist. Groups such as the Peoples independent Republic of New Brighton was formed by Paul Zaaman, The New Brighton Businesses and landowners association spokesperson, in order to protest lack of investment by the Christchurch City Council into New Brighton.\n\nNew Brighton was also named to be the host the finish of the annual Speight's Coast to Coast multisport race in February 2015. The previous finishing point of the race was in Sumner.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.niwa.cri.nz/services/cam-era/sites/piercam/ NIWA: Pier-cam hourly image]\n* [http://library.christchurch.org.nz/Heritage/Photos/Disc3/IMG0001.asp New Brighton Pier, circa 1915, Christchurch City Libraries]\n* [http://www.newbrightonslsc.org.nz/ New Brighton Surf Club ]\n* [http://heritage.christchurchcitylibraries.com/archives/edgeoftheeast-2016/ Edge of the East 2016, Christchurch City Libraries]\n\n{{Christchurch City, New Zealand}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Christchurch]]\n[[Category:Surfing locations in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{advert|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n|name                   = New Brighton\n|image_skyline          = New Brighton Pier, Christchurch.jpg\n|image_caption          = New Brighton Pier, Christchurch\n|pushpin_map            = New Zealand Christchurch\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|area_total_km2         = 2.7891\n|population_as_of       = 2013\n|population_total       = 2442\n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|coordinates            = {{coord|-43.508|172.726|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''New Brighton''' is a coastal suburb of [[Christchurch]], New Zealand, {{convert|8|km|mi}} east of the [[Christchurch Central City|city centre]]. At the 2013 census, it had a population of 2,442. The [[Christchurch earthquake]]s caused significant damage in the area.\n\nNew Brighton is one of eastern Christchurch's main entertainment and tourist centres, with its architecturally unique pier and scenic coastline.\n\n==Naming==\nThe naming of New Brighton was apparently done on a 'spur of moment' decision by William Fee, an early settler of the area. When [[Guise Brittan]], the Waste Lands Commissioner, visited the area in December 1860, he was recognised and Fee chalked 'New Brighton' on a wooden plank, supposedly in reference to his fellow settler Stephen Brooker, who had come from [[New Brighton, Merseyside|New Brighton]] in England.<ref name=\"Christchurch Place Names\">{{cite web|last= Harper|first= Margaret|title= Christchurch Place Names|url= http://christchurchcitylibraries.com/Heritage/PlaceNames/ChristchurchPlaceNames.pdf |publisher=Christchurch City Libraries|accessdate=1 October 2011|date=July 2011|pages = 131f}}</ref> The [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] name for the area is Kaiuau (''kai'' means food and ''aua'' is [[Yellow-eye mullet]])<ref name=\"Reed\">{{cite book\n |last=Reed\n |first=A. W.\n |title=Place Names of New Zealand\n |year=2010\n |publisher=Raupo\n |location=Rosedale, North Shore\n |isbn=978-0-14-320410-7\n |page = 45\n |editor=Peter Dowling\n}}</ref> or O-ruapaeroa (an east wind blowing along the shore).<ref name=\"Christchurch Place Names\" />\n\nThe suburb is frequently referred to simply as Brighton, occasionally leading to confusion with [[Brighton, New Zealand|Brighton]] near [[Dunedin]].\n\n==New Brighton Pier==\n{{main|New Brighton Pier}}\n[[File:New Brighton Pier, New Brighton, New Zealand 02.jpg|thumb|New Brighton Pier in evening light in 2019]]\nThere have been two piers in New Brighton. The first pier, of wooden construction, opened on 18 January 1894 and was demolished on 12 October 1965. The current concrete pier was opened on 1 November 1997.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Brighton Pier |url=http://my.christchurchcitylibraries.com/new-brighton-pier/ |publisher=[[Christchurch City Libraries]] |accessdate=23 April 2016}}</ref> It is one of the icons of Christchurch. The pier was closed for earthquake repairs in 2016 reopened again in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/104337314/new-brighton-pier-reopens-on-saturday-following-85-million-repair|title=New Brighton Pier reopens on Saturday following $8.5 million repair|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe suburb is divided into three sections spread along the southern coast of [[Pegasus Bay]]: North New Brighton; New Brighton; and South New Brighton, which lies at the northern end of a narrow peninsula between the bay and the [[Avon Heathcote Estuary]]. A {{convert|300|m|ft}} [[pier]] was built here in the 1990s, and opened on 1 November 1997.\n\nNew Brighton was originally a distinct coastal village, separated from the then outer suburbs of Christchurch by the swampy areas adjoining the [[Avon River (Canterbury)|Avon River]]. However, urban expansion, land reclamation and drainage have led to Brighton being swallowed by Christchurch city.\n\n==Attractions==\n[[File:New Brighton and the Port Hills, Christchurch, New Zealand, 12 June 2008.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Aerial view of New Brighton beach and the Port Hills]]\n[[File:New Brighton, Christchurch.jpg|thumb|200px|The beach]]\nThe current attractions of the area include:\n* A sandy beach, suitable for surfing, stretching 18&nbsp;km from the [[Waimakariri River]] mouth in the north, to the spit in the south\n* New Brighton's Seaside Market \u2013 held weekly in the pedestrian part of the New Brighton Mall\n* Pier and Council library on the foreshore, in Central New Brighton\n* The New Brighton and Districts Museum, located on Hardy Street\n* Home of the first surf life saving club in New Zealand established in 1910,<ref>{{cite web|title=Centenary|url=http://newbrightonslsc.org.nz/?page_id=16|publisher=New Brighton Surf Bathing & Life Saving Club Incorporated 1910|accessdate=1 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312103442/http://newbrightonslsc.org.nz/?page_id=16|archivedate=12 March 2012}}</ref> also North Beach Surf Club to the north and South New Brighton Surf Club to the south\n* Rawhiti Domain \u2013 with a [[Christchurch City Council]]-run golf links, tennis courts, dog park, rugby fields, cricket ovals, netball courts, community carden, archery club and children's play area\n\n[[Image:NewBrightonPier gobeirne.JPG|left|thumb|400px|New Brighton Pier, library, and clock tower]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Events==\nNew Brighton host a variety of free public events:\n\n===Coast to Coast===\n\nStaged every February, the annual Coast to Coast race finishes at New Brighton. Competitors traverse the island by running, canoeing and cycling.\n\n===New Zealand Sand Castle competition===\n\nHeld in February annually.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n===Kite Day===\n\nHeld in January annually.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n===New Brighton day===\n\nEvery February annually, Happy New Brighton Day is one of the largest community events held in New Brighton.\n\n===Guy Fawkes===\n\nThis is held in November annually. There is a display of Fireworks on the New Brighton Pier, beginning at sunset about 9.00pm, as well as a lights show off the pier and music.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n==Saturday trading==\nFor several decades, New Brighton had the distinction of being the only place in Christchurch where general retail shops were permitted to open on Saturdays<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.christchurch.org.nz/Heritage/Chronology/Year/1946.asp|title=Christchurch \u2013 A Chronology \u2013 1946|publisher=[[Christchurch City Libraries]]|accessdate=14 October 2007}}</ref> (remaining closed on Mondays), and the business district thrived as a result. With the introduction of nationwide Saturday trading in 1980, and then seven-day trading in 1990, retail activity declined significantly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/Places/Canterbury/CanterburyPlaces/9/en |title=East Christchurch|publisher=[[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]] |accessdate=14 October 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Walrond |first1=Carl |title=Food shops \u2013 Shopping hours |url= http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/food-shops/page-7 |publisher=Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand |accessdate=16 October 2014 |date=13 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public transport==\nA variety of bus routes connect the city centre with New Brighton.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.metroinfo.co.nz/map/ |title=Metro |publisher=Metroinfo | access-date=22 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nAs of 2015 there are four operating primary schools in New Brighton. This includes New Brighton Catholic and Rawhiti beach campus in central New Brighton, South New Brighton primary in the south New Brighton and Rawhiti QE2 base in North New Brighton. In early 2015, the Christchurch City Council and the Ministry of Education announced that North New Brighton's QE2 park would be accommodating the new 80 million dollar joint secondary school campus consisting of Shirley Boys and Avonside Girls high schools, along the 39 million dollar Eastern Recreation and sports facility. 2015<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Mayor-not-offended-by-cheeky-protest/tabid/423/articleID/278912/Default.aspx|work=3 News NZ |title= Mayor not offended by 'cheeky' protest| date=3 December 2012| accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Sport and recreation==\nA number of well known sports groups represent the local area. Some of the most notable groups are the New Brighton Rugby club. The New Brighton cricket club and the New Brighton Olympic Athletic club. Other groups include the Christchurch Archery club and New Brighton long boarders club. Also home of the oldest Surf Life Saving Club in New Zealand, The New Brighton Surf Bathing & Life Saving Club, established in 1910.\n\n==Christchurch earthquakes aftermath==\nDue in part to the ground on which it was built, the consequences for New Brighton of the 2011 earthquake did not only relate to building damage.\n[[File:Fish and Chip shop North New Brighton, Christchurch following Feb 2011 quake.jpg|thumb|200px|Fish and Chip shop North New Brighton, Christchurch following Feb 2011 quake]]\n[[File:Liquefaction on roads - North New Brighton centre in Christchurch Feb 2011 quake.jpg|thumb|200px|Liquefaction on roads \u2013 North New Brighton centre in Christchurch Feb 2011 quake]]\nIn December 2012 residents held a protest against the perceived slow progress of rebuilding in the area following [[2011 Christchurch earthquake|the region's damaging earthquakes]], in which 80 people bared their bottoms.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/New-Brighton-residents-protest-bum-deal/tabid/423/articleID/278860/Default.aspx |work=3 News NZ |title= Angry residents hold 'cheeky' protest| date=2 December 2012| accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref> Christchurch Mayor Bob Parker said he wasn't offended, but the residents were \"wrong\". These feelings of neglect by the Christchurch City Council would continue to persist. Groups such as the Peoples independent Republic of New Brighton was formed by Paul Zaaman, The New Brighton Businesses and landowners association spokesperson, in order to protest lack of investment by the Christchurch City Council into New Brighton.\n\nNew Brighton was also named to be the host the finish of the annual Speight's Coast to Coast multisport race in February 2015. The previous finishing point of the race was in Sumner.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.niwa.cri.nz/services/cam-era/sites/piercam/ NIWA: Pier-cam hourly image]\n* [http://library.christchurch.org.nz/Heritage/Photos/Disc3/IMG0001.asp New Brighton Pier, circa 1915, Christchurch City Libraries]\n* [http://www.newbrightonslsc.org.nz/ New Brighton Surf Club ]\n* [http://h