{"title_page": "Friendship Archway", "text_new": "{{Infobox artwork\n| title              = Friendship Archway\n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   = \n| other_title_2      = \n| wikidata           =\n| image              = Chinatown, DC gate.jpg\n| image_upright      = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = The gate in 2004\n| artist             = \n| year               =  <!-- If after 1583 CE, use {{start date|YYYY}} -->\n| completion_date    =  <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| catalogue          = \n| medium             = \n| movement           =\n| subject            = \n| height_metric      =  <!-- (i.e. in metric units) -->\n| width_metric       = \n| length_metric      = \n| diameter_metric    = \n| height_imperial    =  <!-- (i.e. in imperial units) -->\n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| diameter_imperial  = \n| dimensions         = \n| dimensions_ref     = \n| metric_unit        = cm  <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included -->\n| imperial_unit      = in  <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included -->\n| weight             = \n| designation        = \n| condition          = \n| museum             = \n| city               = [[Washington, D.C.]], United States\n| coordinates        = {{Coord|38.89982|-77.021692|type:landmark_region:US-DC|display=inline,title}}\n| owner              = \n| accession          = \n| preceded_by        =  <!-- preceding work by the same artist -->\n| followed_by        =  <!-- next work by the same artist -->\n| module             = \n| website            =  <!-- Official webpage/site only: {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''''Friendship Archway''''' is a gate installed at [[Chinatown (Washington, D.C.)|Chinatown]], [[Washington, D.C.]], United States.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Chinatown, Washington, United States (Unsplash W NJEJY1maI).jpg|thumb|right|Detail, 2016]]\n\nIn 1986, the city dedicated the traditional Chinese gate designed by Alfred H. Liu, a local architect and chairman of the Chinatown Development Corporation, who emigrated from [[Taiwan]] to the United States as a teenager. The colorful, US$1 million work of [[public art]] includes seven roofs up to 60 feet high, 7000 tiles, and 272 painted dragons in the style of the [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] and [[Qing dynasty|Qing]] dynasties. Erected to celebrate friendship with Washington's [[sister city]] of [[Beijing]], it was hoped the arch would reinforce the neighborhood's Chinese character. According to the plaque next to the arch, it is the largest such single-span archway in the world. In 1993, the Friendship Archway underwent a major renovation funded by D.C. and Chinese governments. [[Artisan]]s from China performed extensive repairs on the archway and repainted its decorations.<ref name=friendshiparchway>{{cite web | author=DeFerrari, John| url=http://greatergreaterwashington.org/post/9183/chinatowns-friendship-archway/ | title=Chinatown's Friendship Archway| publisher=Greater Greater Washington| date=February 9, 2011| accessdate=September 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1986 in art]]\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 6]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category inline}}\n\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.|state=collapsed}}\n{{Portal bar|China|United States|Visual arts}}\n\n[[Category:1986 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:1986 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Chinatown, Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Dragons in art]]\n[[Category:Gates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artwork\n| title              = Friendship Archway\n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   = \n| other_title_2      = \n| wikidata           =\n| image              = Chinatown, DC gate.jpg\n| image_upright      = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = The gate in 2004\n| artist             = \n| year               =  <!-- If after 1583 CE, use {{start date|YYYY}} -->\n| completion_date    =  <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| catalogue          = \n| medium             = \n| movement           =\n| subject            = \n| height_metric      =  <!-- (i.e. in metric units) -->\n| width_metric       = \n| length_metric      = \n| diameter_metric    = \n| height_imperial    =  <!-- (i.e. in imperial units) -->\n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| diameter_imperial  = \n| dimensions         = \n| dimensions_ref     = \n| metric_unit        = cm  <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included -->\n| imperial_unit      = in  <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included -->\n| weight             = \n| designation        = \n| condition          = \n| museum             = \n| city               = [[Washington, D.C.]], United States\n| coordinates        = {{Coord|38.89982|-77.021692|type:landmark_region:US-DC|display=inline,title}}\n| owner              = \n| accession          = \n| preceded_by        =  <!-- preceding work by the same artist -->\n| followed_by        =  <!-- next work by the same artist -->\n| module             = \n| website            =  <!-- Official webpage/site only: {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''''Friendship Archway''''' is a gate installed at [[Chinatown (Washington, D.C.)|Chinatown]], [[Washington, D.C.]], United States.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Chinatown, Washington, United States (Unsplash W NJEJY1maI).jpg|thumb|right|Detail, 2016]]\n\nIn 1986, the city dedicated the traditional Chinese gate designed by Alfred H. Liu, a local architect and chairman of the Chinatown Development Corporation, who emigrated from [[Taiwan]] to the United States as a teenager. The colorful, US$1 million work of [[public art]] includes seven roofs up to 60 feet high, 7000 tiles, and 272 painted dragons in the style of the [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] and [[Qing dynasty|Qing]] dynasties. Erected to celebrate friendship with Washington's [[sister city]] of [[Beijing]], it was hoped the arch would reinforce the neighborhood's Chinese character. According to the plaque next to the arch, it is the largest such single-span archway in the world. In 1993, the Friendship Archway underwent a major renovation funded by D.C. and Chinese governments. [[Artisan]]s from China performed extensive repairs on the archway and repainted its decorations.<ref name=friendshiparchway>{{cite web | author=DeFerrari, John| url=http://greatergreaterwashington.org/post/9183/chinatowns-friendship-archway/ | title=Chinatown's Friendship Archway| publisher=Greater Greater Washington| date=February 9, 2011| accessdate=September 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1986 in art]]\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 6]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category inline}}\n\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.|collapsed=yes}}\n{{Portal bar|China|United States|Visual arts}}\n\n[[Category:1986 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:1986 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Chinatown, Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Dragons in art]]\n[[Category:Gates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:fmt", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friendship_Archway"}
{"title_page": "Hugh Egerton", "text_new": "'''Hugh Edward Egerton''' (19 April 1855 \u2013 21 May 1927) was a British historian.\n\nHe was the second son of E. C. Egerton, who was an MP. He as educated at [[Rugby School]] and [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]], where he gained a First Class ''[[Literae humaniores]]'' in 1876. In 1880 he was [[called to the bar]] by the [[Inner Temple]] and worked on the North Wales and Chester Circuit.<ref name=\"Times\">\u2018Mr. H. E. Egerton\u2019, ''The Times'' (23 May 1927), p. 19.</ref> \n\nIn 1885 he was appointed assistant private secretary to [[Edward Stanhope]], who became [[Secretary of State for the Colonies]] in 1886. Stanhope appointed Egerton to the managing committee of the Emigrants Information Office and one of its tasks was to write a handbook on Britain's colonies, which Egerton contributed to. This stimulated his interest in colonial history and he devoted his spare time to researching the topic. This eventually led to his 1897 book, ''A Short History of British Colonial Policy'', which became a standard work and which reached a sixth edition by 1920. It was the first book on the subject to comprehensively survey British colonial history in relation to the political ideas that had shaped it.<ref name=\"Times\" />\n\nIn 1900 he published a biography of Sir [[Stamford Raffles]] and edited a collection of Sir [[William Molesworth]]'s speeches in 1903. In 1905 Egerton was appointed the first [[Beit Professor of Colonial History]] at Oxford, which he held until 1920. He was also appointed a Fellow of [[All Souls College, Oxford]], in 1905.<ref name=\"Times\" />\n\nHe contributed to ''[[The Cambridge Modern History]]'' and edited the Report of the Royal Commission on Loyalists' Claims.<ref name=\"Times\" />\n\nIn 1886 he married Margaret Trotter, with who he had one son and two daughters.<ref name=\"Times\" />\n\n==Works==\n*''A short history of British colonial policy'' (1897).\n*''The origin and growth of greater Britain; an introduction to Sir C.P. Lucas's Historical geography'' (1903).\n*''Federations and unions within the British Empire'' (1911).\n*(editor), ''The Royal Commission on the Losses and Services of American Loyalists, 1783-1785'' (1915).\n*''British foreign policy in Europe to the end of the 19th century; a rough outline'' (1917).\n*''British colonial policy in the XXth century'' (1922).\n*''The causes and character of the American revolution'' (1923).\n*\n*\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Richard Symonds, ''Oxford and Empire: The Last Lost Cause?'' (London: Palgrave Macmillan, 1986). {{ISBN|978-0-333-40206-1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Egerton, Hugh}}\n\n[[Category:1855 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rugby School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Beit Professors of Commonwealth History]]\n[[Category:Fellows of All Souls College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n", "text_old": "'''Hugh Edward Egerton''' (19 April 1855 \u2013 21 May 1927) was a British historian.\n\nHe was the second son of E. C. Egerton, who was an MP. He as educated at [[Rugby School]] and [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]], where he gained a First Class ''[[Literae humaniores]]'' in 1876. In 1880 he was [[called to the bar]] by the [[Inner Temple]] and worked on the North Wales and Chester Circuit.<ref name=\"Times\">\u2018Mr. H. E. Egerton\u2019, ''The Times'' (23 May 1927), p. 19.</ref> \n\nIn 1885 he was appointed assistant private secretary to [[Edward Stanhope]], who became [[Secretary of State for the Colonies]] in 1886. Stanhope appointed Egerton to the managing committee of the Emigrants Information Office and one of its tasks was to be write a handbook on Britain's colonies, which Egerton contributed to. This stimulated his interest in colonial history and he devoted his spare time to researching the topic. This eventually led to his 1897 book, ''A Short History of British Colonial Policy'', which became a standard work and which reached a sixth edition by 1920. It was the first book on the subject to comprehensively survey British colonial history in relation to the political ideas that had shaped it.<ref name=\"Times\" />\n\nIn 1900 he published a biography of Sir [[Stamford Raffles]] and edited a collection of Sir [[William Molesworth]]'s speeches in 1903. In 1905 Egerton was appointed the first [[Beit Professor of Colonial History]] at Oxford, which he held until 1920. He was also appointed a Fellow of [[All Souls College, Oxford]], in 1905.<ref name=\"Times\" />\n\nHe contributed to ''[[The Cambridge Modern History]]'' and edited the Report of the Royal Commission on Loyalists' Claims.<ref name=\"Times\" />\n\nIn 1886 he married Margaret Trotter, with who he had one son and two daughters.<ref name=\"Times\" />\n\n==Works==\n*''A short history of British colonial policy'' (1897).\n*''The origin and growth of greater Britain; an introduction to Sir C.P. Lucas's Historical geography'' (1903).\n*''Federations and unions within the British Empire'' (1911).\n*(editor), ''The Royal Commission on the Losses and Services of American Loyalists, 1783-1785'' (1915).\n*''British foreign policy in Europe to the end of the 19th century; a rough outline'' (1917).\n*''British colonial policy in the XXth century'' (1922).\n*''The causes and character of the American revolution'' (1923).\n*\n*\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Richard Symonds, ''Oxford and Empire: The Last Lost Cause?'' (London: Palgrave Macmillan, 1986). {{ISBN|978-0-333-40206-1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Egerton, Hugh}}\n\n[[Category:1855 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rugby School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Beit Professors of Commonwealth History]]\n[[Category:Fellows of All Souls College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n", "name_user": "Britannicus", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wiki